AGI -&nbsp;
<span> The decision of the British courts &nbsp is awaited for tomorrow; if to grant the founder of WikiLeaks Julian Assange a final appeal against his extradition in the United States, where he is prosecuted for a massive escape of documents according to a law on espionage > of 1917.</span>
&nbsp;
Fourteen years after the massive escape of documents reserved for U.S. military activities, today a decisive day for the 52-year-old Australian in this long case has become a symbol of threats to press freedom. Two judges of the High Court of London, Victoria Sharp and Jeremy Johnson, will have to decide whether or not to grant Julian Assange the right to appeal against his extradition in the United States, agreed in June 2022 by the British Government. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the event of defeat, Julian Assange would bring his case to the European Court of Human Rights > in the hope of obtaining the suspension of extradition, but according to his wife the times seem very close. The U.S. authorities are pursuing Julian Assange for publishing, since 2010, more than 700,000 confidential documents on U.S. military activities and diplomats, especially in Iraq and Afghanistan. Among these, a video showing civilians, including two Reuters journalists, killed by the fire of an American helicopter in Iraq in July 2007. He was arrested by the British police in 2019 after seven years in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, to avoid extradition in Sweden as part of a rape investigation, closed in 2019.
&nbsp;
<h2>- Suicide risk -</h2>
Several voices urged US President Joe Biden to drop the 18 charges against Assange during Donald Trump's first term.
In recent weeks, people close to Julian Assange, who have been detained for five years in the Belmarsh prison in London, have warned that his health is deteriorating.&nbsp; Its defence also emphasizes the risk of suicide in case of extradition.> Malate was absent from the hearings of February, where dozens of his supporters showed their support.
&nbsp;
During the two days of hearing, the lawyers of Julian Assange tried to convince the judges that the case against him was "political" and that extradition would jeopardize his health and even his life. The Australian is prosecuted for the "normal journalistic practice" to "get and publish information", supported his lawyer Edward Fitzgerald.
his client risked a disproportionate condemnation in the United States and "there is the real risk of a blatant denial of justice," he added.
&nbsp;
Lawyer Clair Dobbin, who represents the US government, argued that Assange "published indiscriminately and consciously the names of people who were sources of information for the United States." "It is these facts that distinguish it (from other media), not its political opinions," the lawyer argued.
&nbsp;
In January 2021, the British courts had initially pronounced themselves in favour of WikiLeaks' founder. By citing the risk of suicide, Judge Vanessa Baraitser refused to give way to extradition. However, the decision was subsequently annulled.
&nbsp;
In an attempt to reassure the public about its treatment, the United States declared that it would not be jailed in the ADX prison of Florence (Colorado), nicknamed "Alcatraz delle Montagne Rocciose" >, and that it would receive the necessary clinical and psychological care. The Americans had also ventilated the possibility that he asked for the penalty in Australia. Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese recently denounced the United States' criminal action against Assange and the Australian Parliament approved a motion calling for an end to it.
&nbsp;

