AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;" EU Member States are already spending much more on defence, with an increase of 40% of the defence budget over the past ten years > and a leap of 50 billion euros between 2022 and 2023. However, the EU's 290 billion budget in 2023 represents only 1.7% of our GDP according to the 2% NATO parameter." The Ue High Representative for Foreign and Security Policy, Josep Borrell, wrote this in his blog.
&nbsp;
"In the present geopolitical context, this could be considered a minimum requirement. However, the overall amount of our expenses is not the only amount we have to follow carefully. To use our defence costs efficiently, we also have to worry about filling gaps and avoiding duplication. As I have already said on many occasions, we have to spend more but also better >, and better it means together," Borrell pointed out.
&nbsp;
"In 2022, European armies invested 58 billion in new equipment. For the fourth consecutive year, the 20% of defence expenditure was exceeded. However, only 18% of these defence investments are currently carried out collaboratively, much below the 35% parameter set by the EU Member States themselves in 2007. Since the beginning of the Russian aggression war, 78% of the equipment purchased by the armies of the EU came from third countries. We are also late in investments in Research and Development," said the High Representative.

