AGI - While Israel continues to bomb Rafah and the center of the Gaza Strip, the clash between the UN and the Jewish State explodes, which blocked the entry of the United Nations convoys destined for the famous civilian population of the area.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The United Nations agency for Palestinian refugees (Unrwa>) has announced that at the time and formally banned from Israel any delivery of food aid in the north of the Gaza Strip. "Despite the tragedy that takes place before our eyes, the Israeli authorities have informed the UN that they will no longer approve the UNRWA food convoys in the north" of the territory, announced on X manager Philippe Lazzarini, underlining that the agency remains "the main still of salvation for Palestinian refugees. "
&nbsp;
The agency in fact can no longer distribute aid in this field, where the risk of famine is sharper, from 29 January, has explained its spokesman Juliette Touma. However, it can continue to do so in the southern part. "Impediting the UNrwa to bring food means in fact denying the possibility of survival to people suffering from hunger," said the Director-General of the World Health Organization >(WHO), Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, who asked for an urgent review of this decision.
<h2>The accusations of Tel Aviv and the replica of the Glass Palace</h2>
Israel accused Unrwa of employing "more than 450 terrorists" in Gaza and claims that 12 of its employees were directly involved in the unprecedented attack of Hamas on 7 October on the Israeli soil that unleashed the war in the Gaza Strip.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Secretary-General of the United Nations, Antonio Guterres>, said that Israel's decision is "totally unacceptable". &nbsp; "We see growing consensus in the international community to tell the Israelis that the ceasefire is necessary and I also see an increasing consensus - I heard it in the United States, I heard it from the European Union, not to mention obviously the Muslim world - to clearly tell the Israelis that any land invasion of Rafah could mean a humanitarian disaster," Guterres added, today visiting Jordan.
&nbsp;
"The Secretary-General of the United Nations, Antonio Guterres, today on the Egyptian side of the Rafah Pass, blamed Israel for the humanitarian situation in Gaza, without condemning in any way the Hamas-ISIS terrorists who plunder humanitarian aid, without condemning the UNRWA that cooperates with terrorists - and without asking for the immediate and unconditional release of all Israeli hostages," Israel writes. &nbsp;
Air strikes on Rafah and Deir al Balah</h2>
Palestinians reported that dozens of people were killed in an Israeli air strike on buildings in Rafah and Deir al Balah, in the middle of the Gaza Strip. Hamas radio also reported that the last floor of the Al Shifa hospital was hit by the artillery and that the artillery fire also targeted the Al Amal hospital at Khan Younis.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Israeli troops and Shin Bet forces claim to have arrested so far about 500 "terrorists" of Hamas and Islamic Jihad in the operation at the hospital. The activity in the Al-Amal area continues, in the western part of Khan Yunis, where "more than 20 terrorists have been eliminated in the area in the last 24 hours". Meanwhile, in the last 24 hours Israeli aviation has attacked about 50 terrorist targets throughout the Gaza Strip, including terrorist infrastructure and military buildings. &nbsp;
<h2> For Israel "Hamas is destroying the hospital"</h2>
Israeli military spokesman Daniel Hagari argued, in a speech relaunched via the web, that Hamas is destroying the al-Shifa hospital in Gaza City and repeated the accusation that the Islamist movement uses hospitals as a basis for making war.
&nbsp;
In the three-minute briefing, Hagari added that the Israeli military operation in the hospital complex was "one of the most successful operations since the beginning of the war" and that Israel "arrested hundreds of suspected terrorists with links confirmed with Hamas or Islamic Jihad". "At this moment, the terrorists of Hamas and Islamic Jihad are barricading within the lanes of the al-Shifa hospital. Hamas is destroying the al-Shifa hospital, he's shooting from the inside of the emergency room and the al-Shifa maternity ward and is launching explosive ordnances from the al-Shifa burn department." Hagari doesn't give evidence of what he claims.
<h2>New efforts to cease fire
The United Nations Security Council should today vote for a new draft resolution for an "immediate ceasefire" in Gaza, a request blocked several times by the United States, but in recent weeks they have begun to change tone with their Israeli ally.
&nbsp;
On Friday, Russia and China vetoed a draft resolution of the United States underlining the "necessity" of an "immediate ceasefire" in Gaza linked to the negotiations for the release of hostages captured during the Hamas attack on October 7. It could be a substantial change in the position of the Biden administration, which is under pressure from the public just as the White House leader is engaged in a difficult electoral campaign for re-election.
&nbsp;
Until now, the United States had always opposed the term "fire" in the United Nations resolutions, blocking three different versions. The United States proposal rejected last Friday did not explicitly ask for immediate ceasefire, but used a formulation considered ambiguous by the Arab countries, and also by China and Russia.
&nbsp;
The new draft resolution > is the result of the work of non-permanent members of the Council, who negotiated throughout the weekend with the United States to try to avoid a new failure and expressed some optimism on the outcome of the vote. "I hope the resolution is adopted and the United States does not vote against it," said a diplomat.
&nbsp;
The latest version of the text, visioned by the Afp Sunday, "demands an immediate ceasefire for the month of Ramadan" - started two weeks ago - "which leads to a ceasefire lasting and permanent" and "requires the immediate and unconditional release of all hostages". Unlike the American text rejected Friday, it does not link these demands to the diplomatic efforts of Qatar, the United States and Egypt, although it "recognises" the existence of these talks aimed at a truce accompanied by an exchange of Palestinian hostages and prisoners. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Guterres stressed that the UN Security Council is. "victim of the huge geopolitical divisions" in the world.&nbsp; For this reason, Guterres added that he spoke alongside the Jordanian Foreign Minister, Ayman Safadi, is "so important that the Security Council finally approves a resolution calling for ceasefire in Gaza".
&nbsp;
"It is our duty to do everything possible to mobilize the entire international community. And I see that consensus is emerging in the international community, even in countries that are friends and allies of Israel. I see that a consensus is emerging on the fact that this war must end, I see a consensus emerge that any land offensive against Rafah would lead to a catastrophic humanitarian situation." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
