AGI - Beijing warns: strong measures will be taken against the Philippines if they continue to implement in the South China Sea > "offensive and provocative actions". The defence ministry spokesman, Wu Qian>, called for the cessation of China's "repeal red line challenges".
&nbsp;
According to Wu, the Philippines would violate the agreements signed with interventions on a ship on the Ayungin atoll, which China considers its territory. The spokesman has emphasized that China so far has had a 'moderate' position, but it has warned that the popular army of liberation> is ready to defend the territorial sovereignty and the marine rights of the Asian country.
<h2>Pechino announces military exercises
Meanwhile, the Command of the Southern Theater of the Operations of the Epl announced military exercises in the area. The Chinese government's communiqué follows an accident last Saturday: the Chinese Coast Guard reported having expelled three Filipino ships "illegally" in the adjacent waters of Ayungin's atoll. And again, last Thursday Beijing denounced that 34 Filipino citizens "disembarked illegally" to Cayo Sandy, another island in the South China Sea whose sovereignty is disputed between China and the Philippines.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Philippines, by them. denounce "aggressive actions" by the Chinese Coast Guard near the coral reef off the coasts of Southeast Asia.
&nbsp;
Manila expressed his "strong protest against the aggressive actions taken by the Chinese Coast Guard and the Maritime Militia against the mission of rotation and refueling undertaken by the Philippines in Ayungin Shoal" on Saturday, said the Filipino Department of Foreign Affairs.

